'''Kikuchi Shrine''' (菊池神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in {{ill|Jōnan-ku|ja|城南区|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōnan-ku|qq=}}, {{ill|Fukuoka|ja|福岡市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukuoka|qq=}}, {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|ja|福岡県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukuoka Prefecture|qq=}}. It enshrines {{ill|Kikuchi Taketoki|ja|菊池武時|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kikuchi Taketoki|qq=}}, {{ill|Emperor Nintoku|ja|仁徳天皇|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Nintoku|qq=}}, and {{ill|Haniyasu Ōkami|ja|埴安大神|1=Haniyasu-hiko and Haniyasu-hime|lt=Haniyasu Ōkami|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haniyasu Ōkami|13=User:Immanuelle/Haniyasu-hiko and Haniyasu-hime|qq=}}. The shrine held the Rank of a former {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prefectural Shrine|qq=}}.

== History ==
In the late {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura period|qq=}}, {{ill|Kikuchi Taketoki|ja|菊池武時|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kikuchi Taketoki|qq=}}, who led the movement to overthrow the shogunate under {{ill|Emperor Go-Daigo|ja|後醍醐天皇|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Go-Daigo|qq=}}, died in battle in {{ill|Hakata|ja|博多|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakata|qq=}}. It is said that his head fell near {{ill|Ropponmatsu|ja|六本松|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ropponmatsu|qq=}} and his torso at {{ill|Nanakuma|ja|七隈|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanakuma|qq=}}. A Kofun (dōzuka) was established at the site of his torso, marking the origin of Kikuchi Shrine.

The Kofun fell into neglect during subsequent wars but was rediscovered in {{ill|Tenpō era|ja|天保|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpō era|qq=}} 2 ({{ill|1831|ja|1831st year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1831|qq=}}) by {{ill|Jō Takasada|ja|城武貞|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jō Takasada|qq=}}, a samurai of the {{ill|Fukuoka Domain|ja|福岡藩|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukuoka Domain|qq=}} and a descendant of the Kikuchi clan. He received permission from the domain lord {{ill|Kuroda Nariyuki|ja|黒田斉清|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuroda Nariyuki|qq=}} to erect a gravestone. In {{ill|Tenpō|ja|天保|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpō|qq=}} 3 ({{ill|1832|ja|1832nd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1832|qq=}}), the 500th anniversary of Taketoki's death was commemorated with offerings from the domain lord.

In {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} 2 ({{ill|1869|ja|1869th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1869|qq=}}), a shrine building was constructed on the site by domain lord {{ill|Kuroda Nagachika|ja|黒田長知|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuroda Nagachika|qq=}}. In {{ill|Taishō|ja|大正|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishō|qq=}} 8 ({{ill|1919|ja|1919th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1919|qq=}}), the {{ill|Haniyasu Shrine|ja|埴安神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haniyasu Shrine|qq=}}, the local tutelary shrine of Nanakuma, was relocated and merged here. On March 16, {{ill|Taishō|ja|大正|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishō|qq=}} 11 ({{ill|1922|ja|1922nd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1922|qq=}}), Kikuchi Shrine was officially designated as a {{ill|Village Shrine|ja|村社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Village Shrine|qq=}}, and on April 4, {{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōwa|qq=}} 8 ({{ill|1933|ja|1933rd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1933|qq=}}), it was promoted to the status of a {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prefectural Shrine|qq=}}. On April 7, it was designated as a shrine receiving government offerings, and on April 13, the grand 600th anniversary festival of Taketoki's death was held.

