'''Kikuchi Shrine''' (菊池神社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in [[:en:Jōnan-ku, Fukuoka|Jōnan-ku]], [[:en:Fukuoka|Fukuoka]], [[:en:Fukuoka Prefecture|Fukuoka Prefecture]]. It enshrines {{ill|Kikuchi Taketoki|ja|菊池武時|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kikuchi Taketoki|qq=|comment=changed title based on wikidata|1=Kikuchi Taketoki|WD=Q94316}}, [[:en:Emperor Nintoku|Emperor Nintoku]], and {{ill|Haniyasu Ōkami|ja|埴安大神|1=Haniyasu-hiko and Haniyasu-hime|lt=Haniyasu Ōkami|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haniyasu Ōkami|13=User:Immanuelle/Haniyasu-hiko and Haniyasu-hime|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}. The shrine held the Rank of a former {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|1=Prefectural Shrine|qid=Q90139226}}{{efn|Ken-sha|lt=Ken-sha|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prefectural Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q712534}}.

== History ==
In the late [[:en:Kamakura period|Kamakura period]], {{ill|Kikuchi Taketoki|ja|菊池武時|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kikuchi Taketoki|qq=|comment=changed title based on wikidata|1=Kikuchi Taketoki|WD=Q94316}}, who led the movement to overthrow the shogunate under [[:en:Emperor Go-Daigo|Emperor Go-Daigo]], died in battle in {{ill|Hakata|ja|博多|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakata|qq=|1=Hakata|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11284628}}. It is said that his head fell near {{ill|Ropponmatsu|ja|六本松|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ropponmatsu|qq=|1=Ropponmatsu|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11392404}} and his torso at {{ill|Nanakuma|ja|七隈|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanakuma|qq=|1=Nanakuma|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11353727}}. A Kofun (dōzuka) was established at the site of his torso, marking the origin of Kikuchi Shrine.

The Kofun fell into neglect during subsequent wars but was rediscovered in [[:en:Tenpō|Tenpō era]] 2 ([[:en:1831|1831]]) by {{ill|Jō Takasada|ja|城武貞|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jō Takasada|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, a samurai of the [[:en:Fukuoka Domain|Fukuoka Domain]] and a descendant of the Kikuchi clan. He received permission from the domain lord {{ill|Kuroda Nariyuki|ja|黒田斉清|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuroda Nariyuki|qq=|1=Kuroda Nariyuki|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11678605}} to erect a gravestone. In [[:en:Tenpō|Tenpō]] 3 ([[:en:1832|1832]]), the 500th anniversary of Taketoki's death was commemorated with offerings from the domain lord.

In [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]] 2 ([[:en:1869|1869]]), a shrine building was constructed on the site by domain lord [[:en:Kuroda Nagatomo|Kuroda Nagachika]]. In [[:en:Taishō era|Taishō]] 8 ([[:en:1919|1919]]), the {{ill|Haniyasu Shrine|ja|埴安神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haniyasu Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, the local tutelary shrine of Nanakuma, was relocated and merged here. On March 16, [[:en:Taishō era|Taishō]] 11 ([[:en:1922|1922]]), Kikuchi Shrine was officially designated as a {{ill|Village Shrine|ja|村社|lt=Son-sha|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Village Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q712534}}, and on April 4, [[:en:Shōwa era|Shōwa]] 8 ([[:en:1933|1933]]), it was promoted to the status of a {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|1=Prefectural Shrine|qid=Q90139226}}{{efn|Ken-sha|lt=Ken-sha|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prefectural Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q712534}}. On April 7, it was designated as a shrine receiving government offerings, and on April 13, the grand 600th anniversary festival of Taketoki's death was held.

